## Error Handling

| Symptom | Action |
|---|---|
| Credential write fails | macOS: check the login keychain is unlocked. Windows: ensure `keyring` is installed (`pip install keyring`). Linux: ensure a Secret Service backend is running (`pip install keyring secretstorage`). |
| Env var empty after source | macOS/Linux: remind user to run `source ~/.zshenv` in a real terminal (not with `!`). Windows: env var is optional — `ts` reads from Credential Manager directly. |
| 401 / 403 on `ts auth whoami` | Wrong or expired credential. Token: get a fresh one (U → Refresh credential). Run `ts auth logout --profile {name}` to clear the stale cache first. |
| DNS / connection refused | URL is wrong or instance unreachable. Check with U → Update URL. |
| `SSLCertVerificationError` | Internal/dev cluster with self-signed cert. Manually add `"verify_ssl": false` to the profile entry in `~/.claude/thoughtspot-profiles.json`. Do not use on production instances. |

---

## Technical Reference

Other skills use the `ts` CLI for all ThoughtSpot API calls. The CLI handles token
caching, credential store access, and expiry automatically.

```bash
# macOS / Linux — verify profile
source ~/.zshenv && ts auth whoami --profile {profile_name}

# Windows
ts auth whoami --profile {profile_name}

# Common API calls
ts metadata search --profile {profile_name} --subtype WORKSHEET --name "%keyword%"
ts tml export {guid} --profile {profile_name} --fqn --associated
ts connections list --profile {profile_name}
```

Token cache: `tempfile.gettempdir()/ts_token_{slug}.txt` (permissions 600 on POSIX).
Skills do not manage this file — use `ts auth logout --profile {name}` to invalidate.

